                    "description": "At the Materials' Physics and Chemistry section in the Quality Department of the European Space Agency, main tasks include: \n- To provide engineering support in the area of Materials, namely in Environmental testing as well as Cleanliness & Contamination Control (CCC); \n- To participate in different Non-Conformance Review Boards;\n- To assess and match customers\u2019 needs to the laboratory/analysis capabilities; proposing/executing test methods to satisfy requirements;\n- To evaluate future investment concepts/ideas, while aiding to identify future needs and methodologies;\n- To design and implement state of the art testing facilities & dedicated ad-hoc set-ups for materials and processes verification testing (including in-situ analysis techniques);\n- To perform materials tests in state of the art vacuum facilities in the areas of Environmental Testing, Outgassing, and Contamination (e.g. UV/VUV/ proton/ electron exposure; thermal endurance; performance degradation of optical surfaces due to contamination deposit).\n- To perform sample characterizations by different techniques, such as Optical/Confocal Microscopy, GC/MS, Raman spectroscopy, UV/Vis/NIR spectroscopy, IR spectroscopy. \n-Thermo-optical properties measurement and evaluation (emittance, solar absorptance). \n- Documentation preparation: Test report, Test procedures, Work Instructions, ISO 17025 documentation preparation.\n-Overall broad knowledge in vacuum technology and ground testing capabilities/limitations.\n-Being familiar with several ECSS standards, Quality Assurance procedures and overall ESA's policies.",
